# Cross-platform line-ending policy.
#
# Without this, `core.autocrlf=true` on Windows checks out committed-LF text as
# CRLF in the working tree. The byte-exact golden / `*_in_sync` tests (descriptor
# goldens, error-codes JS, oisi.schema.json, …) compare against output the Rust
# generators emit with LF, so a CRLF checkout makes them fail on Windows CI while
# passing on Linux/macOS. Normalize ALL text to LF in the repo and the working
# tree on every platform so byte-exact comparisons hold identically everywhere.
* text=auto eol=lf

# Binary assets / fixtures — never apply line-ending conversion (would corrupt them).
*.oisi   binary
*.bin    binary
*.h5     binary
*.hdf5   binary
*.mat    binary
*.npy    binary
*.png    binary
*.jpg    binary
*.jpeg   binary
*.gif    binary
*.ico    binary
*.icns   binary
*.pdf    binary
*.woff   binary
*.woff2  binary
*.ttf    binary
*.otf    binary

# Windows-only scripts must stay CRLF to run natively under cmd/PowerShell.
*.bat    text eol=crlf
*.cmd    text eol=crlf
*.ps1    text eol=crlf
